  <!-- ═══ RIGOR CHECKS ═══ -->
  <section class="py-12 md:py-16" id="rigor">
    <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mb-8">
      <div class="h-px flex-1 bg-[var(--color-border)]"></div>
      <h2 class="text-lg sm:text-xl font-bold font-[family-name:var(--font-heading)] text-[var(--color-text-primary)] whitespace-nowrap">
        Rigor Checks
      </h2>
      <div class="h-px flex-1 bg-[var(--color-border)]"></div>
    </div>

    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] max-w-2xl mx-auto text-center mb-8">
      Not everyone agrees on the scope or urgency of neurorights. These voices sharpen the field.
    </p>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 max-w-5xl mx-auto">
      <div class="glass rounded-xl p-5 border border-[var(--color-border)]">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-[var(--color-text-primary)] mb-2">Neuromodesty</h3>
        <p class="text-xs text-[var(--color-text-muted)] leading-relaxed mb-2">
          Stephen Morse (2006) warned that neuroscience claims are routinely overclaimed when applied to law.
          "Brain Overclaim Syndrome" cautions against assuming neural correlates prove causation or eliminate agency.
        </p>
        <p class="text-[10px] text-[var(--color-text-faint)]">
          QIF response: we score signal-level interference, not mental states. NISS measures physical amplitude disruption,
          not "thought harm."
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="glass rounded-xl p-5 border border-[var(--color-border)]">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-[var(--color-text-primary)] mb-2">Premature Legislation</h3>
        <p class="text-xs text-[var(--color-text-muted)] leading-relaxed mb-2">
          Anna Wexler (2024) argues the neurorights movement risks legislating solutions to problems that don't yet exist,
          potentially creating regulatory barriers to beneficial research.
        </p>
        <p class="text-[10px] text-[var(--color-text-faint)]">
          QIF response: technical specifications are not legislation. Standards (like CVSS) inform but don't mandate.
          Building the fire code doesn't close the building.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="glass rounded-xl p-5 border border-[var(--color-border)]">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-[var(--color-text-primary)] mb-2">Anti-Inflationism</h3>
        <p class="text-xs text-[var(--color-text-muted)] leading-relaxed mb-2">
          Marcello Ienca (2021) warned that multiplying neurorights beyond what existing human rights frameworks already cover
          risks diluting protections. Better to extend existing rights than create new ones.
        </p>
        <p class="text-[10px] text-[var(--color-text-faint)]">
          QIF response: we extend Mental Privacy and Mental Integrity with technical depth, not new rights. Five rights, not fifteen.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

